default defaultThe British Board of Film Classification (BBFC) is grateful for the opportunity to respond to the Culture
default,
default Media and Sport Committee Inquiry into Online Safety.  
default  default1.2 The BBFC is an independent, non-governme
defaultntal body which classifies films and videos distributed by way of packaged media and, increasingly, on the internet.  
defaultThe BBFC’s
default primary aim is to protect children and other vulnerable groups from harm through classification decisions which are legally enf
defaultorceable and to empower consumers, particularly parents and children, through content information and education.  
defaultThe BBFC will not classify material which is illegal in the UK, including content which promotes terrorism or which features indecent images o
defaultf children.
default  The BBFC became the independent regulator of content delivered by mobile networks in the UK from 2 September 2013.  The Director of the BBFC, David Cooke, sits on the Executive Board of UK Council for Child Internet Safety 
default(UKCCIS) 
defaultin recognit
defaultion of the BBFC’s role in the protection of children online. 
default1.3 The BBFC classifies films and videos/DVDs according to its Classification Guidelines, with ratings ranging from U for Universal to R18 which are restricted videos only allowed to be sold in 
defaultlicensed sex shops.  The BBFC’s Guidelines are the result of extensive public consultation 
defaultwith over 
default1
default0,000 people across the UK being consulted during the most recent Guidelines consultation
default in 2013
default.
default   Research demonstrates that the public agrees with the
default BBFC’s classification decisions 
defaultmost of the time.  92% of recent film viewers agreed with classification of films they had seen recently.
default (
defaultGoldstone Perl, 
defaultBernice Hardie 
default20
default13
default); and recognises and understands the BBFC’s symbols 89% of the time (rising to 9
default7% for parents) (
defaultTNS, 2007
default).   
default1.4  The BBFC also publishes (on its website and Apps) more detailed information, BBFCinsight, aimed primarily at parents, which outlines the key content issues in a film and thereby enables viewers to make fully educated vi
defaultewing decisions for themselves and their families. This information is available both when the content is distributed by way of packaged media and online. Independent research (
defaultSlesenger, 2009
default) suggests that 86% of parents of primary schoolchildren find th
defaultis information useful. 
